SIMPLE: relinquish
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Relinquish
<hw>Re*lin"quish</hw> <pr>(-kw?sh)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Relinquished</conjf>
<pr>(-kw?sht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Relinquishing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>relinquir</ets>,
L. <ets>relinquere</ets> to leave behind; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re +
<ets>linquere</ets> to leave. See <er>Loan</er>, and cf. <er>Relic</er>,
<er>Relict</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To withdraw from; to leave behind; to desist from;
to abandon; to quit; <as>as, to <ex>relinquish</ex> a
pursuit</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We ought to <qex>relinquish</qex> such rites.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They placed Irish tenants upon the lands <qex>relinquished</qex>
by the English.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give up; to renounce a claim to; resign; <as>as,
to <ex>relinquish</ex> a debt</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To resign; leave; quit; forsake; abandon; desert;
renounce; forbear; forego. See <er>Resign</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Relinquisher</ent>⟦br⟧
